title: For Sale:  Dueling pistol - 1840s british hand engraved percussion pistol - beautiful!
postcontent:
1840s british dueling pistol from known maker!

This is NOT a reproduction.

Gun is over 150 years old and functions.

Pistol is marked with the name of the maker, street and city (Robert Jones of  Howard street, Liverpool). Gun is also marked with the Birmingham proof/inspection mark used between 1812-1904.

Robert jones' firearms company was active from 1827-1917 in Liverpool. He is is well known maker of shotguns. This is the first dueling pistol I have seen of his.

This was made prior to the American civil war.

Gun cocks and trigger works. Ram rod is on a swing arm and functions appropriately.

Most every part of this gun has hand engraving. It's truly a work of art. Handle, barrel, trigger guard, hammer, base plate. This would have taken a master craftsman a good deal of time.

As the gun is original, it has wear. Dings here and there. There's one mark on the bottom of the barrel which I think might be a hallmark, but can't tell. Could be a small pit. Base plate of the handle has at some point been used like a hammer and has dings as a result. Hammer bell where it would land on a cap has a a split from being dry fired too much. Please see pictures.

I'm willing to trade for working modern firearms. But prefer cash. I do not need any more antiques.

I do not accept checks and you are not "test firing" this pistol. Dry fire fine. I do not ship guns either. Serious offers only.

title: For Sale:  World War II German Luftwaffe Helmet, Type M1940
location: South Orange County, Orange County, California
postcontent:
Stamped inside the helmet rim are the following markers, Lot 1345, hkp64.  The hkp64 indicates the helmet is size 64.

This helmet was purchased from an antique store in the 1980s and has been in room temperature storage since that time.

The M1940 helmet first appeared in March 1940 following a redesign of the manufacturing process which now incorporated more automated stamping techniques.  The first helmets issued received only one decal on the left side of the helmet.  In 1943 this factory applied decal was discontinued in order to comply with orders issued by the Supreme Commander of the Wehrmacht.  Helmets of this type are characteristic of having rolled edges and stamped air vents that are embossed directly into the steel shell.  Paint finishes range from medium to very dark blue-grey in overall tone with semi-rough to rough outer texture. 

The helmet has a decal of a bird carrying a symbol in its left talon that is standard for this period Luftwaffe helmet.

title: For Sale:  GLOCK 19 GEN-4 9MM Fixed Sights, 15RD 3 MAGS
postcontent:
SO WHY CHOOSE A GEN 4 OVER A GEN 3?

The Gen 4 has an initially smaller grip than the Gen3, and comes with two different backstraps to adjust the grip to your liking. Most seem to prefer no backstraps. The 1st backstrap makes the grip the same size as a Gen 3 gun and the second one makes it a bit larger. This is the one I actually prefer on my G17 so far. 

Next, the recoil spring has gone from a single spring to a dual spring setup to lessen the felt recoil and to reduce stress on the frames in .40 guns and above. Theoretically, Glock .40 pistols were guns adapted from 9mm. Now the theory is the Gen4's were designed more around the .40 cartridge. This originally caused issues with the new 9mm variations of the Gen 4's due to the fact that they tried to use the same spring for both, making the 9mm's only truly reliable with the higher energy 9mm rounds out there and made them highly susceptible to limp-wristing. 

Another change is the grip surface. It has a new, more aggressive gripping surface to make the guns easier to hold onto with sweaty hands or worse. It works quite well but can be a bit abrasive if you use an IWB holster. I also believe the finger grooves are a little less aggressive than the original finger grooves. 

Last but not least, Gen4's have a larger mag release that is now also reversible.
